<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Mind says, the Body follows<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.72)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10837'>Umapathee "Chen" Chenthuran</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10837&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 27, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> The mental side of any event in life often is underestimated, whether it is with exams, driving along the highway or playing in a major LOTR event. Your actions are, (generally), dictated by your brain. Your brain is an instrumental tool in life. Without it, you cannot function. <br>
<br>
Your brain is a supercomputer beyond human comprehension. It enables you to reason, make judgements, communicate, innovate. It dictates your personality. Nobody uses their brain to it&#8217;s full potential. We can all improve though. Here&#8217;s how&#8230;<br>
<br>
&#8220;The mind says, the body follows.&#8221;<br>
<br>
You need to take care of your brain. You can overcome panic and pressure if you use your brain in the right way. <br>
<br>
Stress and panic decreases the efficiency of your actions. The key to the equation is routine. Sounds silly? Every person under pressure has routine to fall back on:<br>
<br>
The First-Aider has the DR ABC.<br>
The Golfer has the 6-point swing.<br>
The Sprinter has the &#8216;sprint phases&#8217;.<br>
The Fireman has protocol to follow<br>
<br>
Why does this work? In a nutshell minimal effort, maximal output. This is called efficiency. Routine gives the brain less information to process at a given time. Therefore the overall product, (ie. Decisions made), are improved. Take one step at a time - use your brain efficiently.<br>
<br>
How does this translate into LOTR? Think about it &#8211; every turn in LOTR has a set routine. This is:<br>
<br>
Start of Turn<br>
Fellowship<br>
Shadow<br>
Manoeuvre Actions<br>
Assignment Actions<br>
Assignment Phase<br>
Archery Actions<br>
Archery Phase <br>
Skirmish Actions<br>
Skirmish Phase<br>
Regroup Actions<br>
Regroup Phase<br>
<br>
Whew! That&#8217;s quite a routine to the unitiated. Hence why so many mistakes are made, even by the top players.<br>
<br>
Think about this situation. You are in the World Championship Finals. You are playing against somebody who plays to win. One mistake and they won&#8217;t let you take it back. One mistake could cost you financial security. Your family depends on this. Your palms are sweating, your thoughts are racing. Your hands are shaking. You can barely hold your cards.<br>
<br>
My thoughts? Take control of the situation. If you lose, lose because your opponent beats you, not because you beat yourself. Dictate the routine. There is order to be found within this chaos&#8230;<br>
<br>
Take a deep breath, block out all other thoughts in your head and focus. Make a conscious effort to take your time. Be meticulous. Ironically, this will speed up your game once you get used to the &#8216;routine&#8217; - your actions are more methodical and efficient. Leave the majority of your cranial efforts to deal with more tricky issues such as decision-making. This is my routine, but for the sake of time bear in mind it&#8217;s from the perspective of the FP player. <br>
<br>
The most important thing to do is &#8216;define&#8217; each phase. Say the name aloud, so your brain makes a &#8216;mental note&#8217; and you&#8217;re less likely to overlook something. Your opponent will appreciate being given the opportunity to perform their actions at the right time too, which promotes positive gaming experience. <br>
<br>
Combined with courtesy to your opponent and a simple, &#8220;Well played&#8221; or &#8220;Good Game&#8221; and/or handshake the best games I&#8217;ve ever had have been based upon this.<br>
<br>
START OF TURN<br>
<br>
&#8220;The easiest time to make unnecessary game-losing mistakes&#8221;<br>
<br>
Say, &#8220;Start of Turn&#8221; out loud. Stop. Gather your thoughts. <br>
<br>
Look at your fellowship. Where are they? If at sanctuary heal 5 wounds.<br>
Look at your allies. Can they heal themselves/be healed by other allies/Frodo OBH? <br>
<br>
That&#8217;s it. Problem solved. No excuse to make mistakes here.<br>
<br>
FELLOWSHIP<br>
<br>
Say, &#8220;Fellowship Phase&#8221; out loud. This prevents confusion with the start of turn actions and focuses your thoughts.<br>
<br>
This is the easiest phase when you are the FP player. Most of your actions are from hand. Your brain is constantly referencing from the cards in hand, so mistakes are difficult to make. Pay attention to any FP abilities your characters/conditions may possess though.<br>
<br>
To avoid confusion, once finished say &#8220;Done&#8221;.<br>
<br>
SHADOW<br>
<br>
Again, an easy phase. If you are the FP player, look at what your opponent does, but take the time for a mental rest. This is your opponent&#8217;s phase, not yours. Don&#8217;t fatigue your brain unnecessarily.<br>
<br>
If you are the shadow player there may be decisions to make depending on your deck. The only advice I can really give to you at this point is not to rush, take your time, make decisions appropriately. Consider the possibilities and situation before committing to an action. <br>
<br>
Once finished say, &#8220;Done&#8221;. Move onto&#8230;<br>
<br>
MANOEUVRE PHASE<br>
<br>
The phases from Manoeuvre onwards really need clarifying if you want to be playing near to your best. It&#8217;s also a way of getting around the unscrupulous opponent trying to enforce a &#8216;skipped&#8217; phase, resulting in a loss of ARV, Shoulder to Shoulder or Sting potential, (during regroup) actions.<br>
<br>
Say, &#8220;Manoeuvre Phase&#8221; out loud. Stop, gather your thoughts.<br>
<br>
If you are the FP player, look at the cards on the table and in hand. NOW is the time to think ahead. What information do you have? You can see all of your cards, whether they be in hand or in play. Don&#8217;t forget about them.<br>
<br>
You can also see the cards your opponent has in play. In addition, if you&#8217;ve used an ability such as Sting/Glamdring you should also know most if not all of the cards your opponent has in hand. Use the information you&#8217;ve gathered, process it with your brain and make a plan of action, thinking of manoeuvres to archery to skirmishes. Think about how you&#8217;re dealing with each individual minion and event. Are you then in a strong enough position to move again?<br>
<br>
Take into account the unexpected, although with information about the opponent&#8217;s hand the likelihood of this should be near zero.<br>
<br>
If you feel that this is the appropriate time to make a manoeuvre action then make one. Otherwise don&#8217;t. Say, &#8220;I have no actions.&#8221; After your action/non-action look at your opponent and ask, &#8220;do you have any manoeuvre actions?&#8221; <br>
<br>
If they do, let them carry them out and assess the situation. If no, and there have been two passed actions move onto the next phase.<br>
<br>
If your opponent has forgotten to make a manoeuvre action whilst you&#8217;re doing this (in a competitive tournament), then don&#8217;t let them go back. You&#8217;ve given them the opportunity to do so which they&#8217;ve neglected to use. Mistakes are all part of the game. Make sure you aren&#8217;t the one making them!<br>
<br>
ARCHERY PHASE<br>
<br>
Begin by saying, &#8220;archery actions&#8221;.<br>
<br>
This phase should have been made easier by forward planning during manoeuvre. Remember to give your opponent the opportunity for archery actions every time you make one &#8211; particularly if they&#8217;re playing Moria Archery and &#8220;Bitter Hatred&#8221; in their deck. Think ahead to the archery phase&#8230;<br>
<br>
Say, &#8220;Archery phase&#8221;<br>
<br>
Tot up the archery totals and assign wounds accordingly. Think about what you&#8217;re doing, particularly against Sauron decks. That&#8217;s it!<br>
<br>
ASSIGNMENT PHASE<br>
<br>
Say, &#8220;Assignment actions&#8221;<br>
<br>
These actions are the least used in LOTR, but that&#8217;s not to say that they should be overlooked! Give you and your opponent the opportunity to make them. If you forget to use &#8216;Frenzy&#8217; or &#8216;Toldea&#8217;, you&#8217;ve just lost a landmark opportunity to take control of the game!<br>
<br>
Once 2 passes occur, say, &#8220;Assignment Phase.&#8221; Assign characters and minions accordingly. Remember to use information about cards in play and hand(s) before committing to an action. Move onto&#8230;<br>
<br>
SKIRMISH PHASE<br>
<br>
This phase is different to the others as each skirmish is resolved one at a time. However, not everyone knows that Skirmish events/actions don&#8217;t have to be used in the same skirmish that is being resolved:<br>
<br>
(Eg. You are playing with Uruks and can spot 5 companions. You have 2 Savageries in hand. Your opponent chooses to resolve a particular skirmish. You play Savagery, (gives Str +4 and fierce until regroup if you can spot 5 companions, otherwise Str +2) &#8211; hence that companion is about to die and reduce the companion number to 4. You can play a second Savagery on ANOTHER unresolved skirmish before the current skirmish resolves to get the maximum bonus before the companion number gets reduced. Controversial, but this has been asked many times on the Decipher message boards&#8230;)<br>
<br>
Just bear the above in mind when thinking about your skirmishes. Other examples include Sauron direct damage minions and Denzien&#8217;s Enraged.<br>
<br>
Say, &#8220;Skirmish Phase&#8221;<br>
<br>
If you are the FP player, choose a skirmish to resolve. Choose the order of skirmishes carefully. <br>
<br>
Firstly, consider whether you can/need to play any skirmish actions or events. Think about what you&#8217;re doing. Give your opponent the opportunity to play any skirmish events immediately after yours. Ask them, &#8220;Do you have any Skirmish Events?&#8221; If 2 passes occur in a row, resolve the skirmish and move onto the next one. Repeat until all of the skirmishes/fierce skirmishes have been resolved. Move onto&#8230;<br>
<br>
REGROUP PHASE<br>
<br>
Firstly, say, &#8220;Regroup actions&#8221;<br>
<br>
Don&#8217;t let the shadow player reconcile his/her hand at this point. It&#8217;s very important! If you use Sting, you look at an opponent&#8217;s hand at this point BEFORE they reconcile.<br>
<br>
If you have a regroup action, such as Sting or An Able Guide then use it when appropriate. Give your opponent the opportunity for regroup actions too. This action phase will become more important when Realms comes out, particularly with Calagin and the new Isengard Orcs. Once two passes occur&#8230;<br>
<br>
Say, &#8220;Regroup Phase&#8221;. Reconcile hand if you are the shadow player. If you are the FP player consider whether you are in a position to move again. Reconcile your hand if not.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
These are the thought processes that go through my mind during every game. It&#8217;s taken me over 1000 words and hours of my time to get them down onto paper. Your brain is capable of doing the above in a matter of seconds, provided it is used in the right way. <br>
<br>
Give yourself the best preparation mentally before a big tournament. This can be as simple as going to bed early, relaxing and making travel plans well in advance of a big event<br>
<br>
Whatever you do in life, routines are essential. They focus your mind, and enable clarity of thought to be present for decisions to be made. My advice is to make your own, and follow them. You&#8217;ll find yourself a better player and a more efficient individual as a result.<br>
<br>
MISCELLANEOUS<br>
<br>
Manoeuvre - English Spelling<br>
Response Actions - Not mentioned but don&#39;t forget them!<br>
<br>
Thanks for Reading<br>
Umapathee Chenthuran<br>
